The area is bordered to the north by Tenjinmae-chō and consists of four sections arranged southward: 1-chōme (up to {{ill|Manjuji Street|ja|万寿寺通|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), 2-chōme (up to {{ill|Gojō Street|ja|五条通|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), 3-chōme (up to {{ill|Yōbai Street|ja|楊梅通|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), and 4-chōme (up to Rokujō Street).

In the 18th year of the Tenshō era (1590), {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft}} implemented a redesign of Kyoto, known as the {{ill|Tenshō Land Division|ja|天正の地割|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, constructing a new street through the precincts of Gojō Tenjin Shrine. As the shrine was also called Tenshi Shrine, this street was named Tenshitsukinuke Street. According to the 1915 ''Kyōto Bōmeishi,'' Tenshitsukinuke Street initially extended from {{ill|Takatsuji Street|ja|高辻通|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to {{ill|Bukkoji Street|ja|仏光寺通|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, later being extended to {{ill|Shio-kōji Street|ja|塩小路通|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

During the Edo period, 1-chōme and 2-chōme belonged to Kawanishi Ku-chōgumi Tomi San-chōgumi, 3-chōme to Kawanishi Ku-chō Izumi-gumi, and 4-chōme to Kawanishi Ku-chō Nakasuji-gumi. In the Meiji era, the area underwent administrative changes, becoming part of the 13th group, the 17th district, and eventually incorporated into Shimogyō Ward in 1879.

== Notable residents and works ==
* {{ill|Mutsumi Tsūzaki|ja|通崎睦美|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A resident of Tenshitsukinuke who authored essays like ''Tenshitsukinuke 1-Chōme: Kimono and Bicycles.''
* {{ill|Tatsuya Yoshimura|ja|吉村達也|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A novelist who wrote ''Kyoto Tenshitsukinuke-dōri no Koi'' (Kyoto's Love on Tenshitsukinuke Street).
* {{ill|Masashi Yamada (director)|ja|山田雅史|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A film director who produced ''Tenshitsukinuke Rokuchōme.''

