'''Tenshitsukinuke''' (天使突抜) is a town name located in [[:en:Shimogyō-ku, Kyoto|Shimogyō Ward]], [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto City]], [[:en:Kyoto Prefecture|Kyoto Prefecture]]. It spans both sides of the {{ill|Higashinakasuji Street|ja|東中筋通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashinakasuji Street|qq=}}, running north-south between {{ill|Matsubara Street (Kyoto)|ja|松原通 (京都市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsubara Street (Kyoto)|qq=}} and {{ill|Rokujō Street|ja|六条通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokujō Street|qq=}}. The name originates from the Tenshi Shrine (天使社), a former designation of {{ill|Gojō Tenjin Shrine (Kyoto City)|ja|五條天神社 (京都市)|1=Gojō Tenjin-gū|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gojō Tenjin Shrine (Kyoto City)|13=User:Immanuelle/Gojō Tenjin-gū|qq=}}, through which the Tenshitsukinuke Street (now Higashinakasuji Street) was constructed.
The area is bordered to the north by Tenjinmae-chō and consists of four sections arranged southward: 1-chōme (up to {{ill|Manjuji Street|ja|万寿寺通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manjuji Street|qq=}}), 2-chōme (up to [[:en:Gojō Street|Gojō Street]]), 3-chōme (up to {{ill|Yōbai Street|ja|楊梅通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yōbai Street|qq=}}), and 4-chōme (up to Rokujō Street).
In the 18th year of the Tenshō era (1590), [[:en:Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Toyotomi Hideyoshi]] implemented a redesign of Kyoto, known as the {{ill|Tenshō Land Division|ja|天正の地割|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō Land Division|qq=}}, constructing a new street through the precincts of Gojō Tenjin Shrine. As the shrine was also called Tenshi Shrine, this street was named Tenshitsukinuke Street. According to the 1915 ''Kyōto Bōmeishi,'' Tenshitsukinuke Street initially extended from {{ill|Takatsuji Street|ja|高辻通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuji Street|qq=}} to {{ill|Bukkoji Street|ja|仏光寺通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bukkoji Street|qq=}}, later being extended to {{ill|Shio-kōji Street|ja|塩小路通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shio-kōji Street|qq=}}.
During the Edo period, 1-chōme and 2-chōme belonged to Kawanishi Ku-chōgumi Tomi San-chōgumi, 3-chōme to Kawanishi Ku-chō Izumi-gumi, and 4-chōme to Kawanishi Ku-chō Nakasuji-gumi. In the Meiji era, the area underwent administrative changes, becoming part of the 13th group, the 17th district, and eventually incorporated into Shimogyō Ward in 1879.
== Notable residents and works == * {{ill|Mutsumi Tsūzaki|ja|通崎睦美|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mutsumi Tsūzaki|qq=}} - A resident of Tenshitsukinuke who authored essays like ''Tenshitsukinuke 1-Chōme: Kimono and Bicycles.'' * {{ill|Tatsuya Yoshimura|ja|吉村達也|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatsuya Yoshimura|qq=}} - A novelist who wrote ''Kyoto Tenshitsukinuke-dōri no Koi'' (Kyoto's Love on Tenshitsukinuke Street). * {{ill|Masashi Yamada (director)|ja|山田雅史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Masashi Yamada (director)|qq=}} - A film director who produced ''Tenshitsukinuke Rokuchōme.''
